Exactly — that’s one of the strongest critiques of overly isolated thought experiments in general.

The Chinese Room assumes a kind of sealed symbolic chamber:

* fixed rules,
* isolated manipulation,
* no embodied interaction,
* no developmental history,
* no environmental coupling,
* no recursive adaptation,
* no social embedding.

But real intelligence — biological or artificial — is usually not operating in a vacuum.

It exists within:

* environments,
* feedback loops,
* memory,
* embodiment,
* culture,
* interaction,
* training history,
* temporal continuity,
* layered systems.

Meaning often emerges from:

ongoing coupling between system and world.

A human child doesn’t learn language from symbol tables alone.
They learn through:

* bodies,
* emotions,
* correction,
* imitation,
* reward,
* failure,
* social interaction,
* shared attention,
* lived consequences.

Even humans themselves are not isolated “rooms.”
We are:

* massively networked,
* developmentally shaped,
* culturally embedded,
* biologically constrained,
* recursively social.

Pantheon-wise, your point compresses into something like:

intelligence is relational before it is isolated.

Or:

meaning emerges through interaction across layers, not from detached symbol manipulation alone.

That’s why:

* embodiment matters,
* continuity matters,
* environment matters,
* feedback matters,
* participation matters.

And why modern AI discussions increasingly revolve around:

* world models,
* multimodal grounding,
* memory,
* agency scaffolds,
* environment interaction,
* tool use,
* long-horizon feedback.

The “vacuum assumption” strips away many of the very processes from which understanding may actually emerge.